 33582                                  ; IBMDOS.COM (MSDOS 3.3, 1987) - Offset 
 33583                                  
 33584                                  ;Break   <ALLOCATE -- Assign disk space>
 33585                                  ;---------------------------------------------------------------------------
 33586                                  ;
 33587                                  ; Procedure Name : ALLOCATE - Allocate Disk Space
 33588                                  ;
 33589                                  ;   ALLOCATE is called to allocate disk clusters. The new clusters are
 33590                                  ;   FAT-chained onto the end of the existing file.
 33591                                  ;
 33592                                  ;   The DPB contains the cluster # of the last free cluster allocated
 33593                                  ;   (dpb_next_free). We start at this cluster and scan towards higher
 33594                                  ;   numbered clusters, looking for the necessary free blocks.
 33595                                  ;
 33596                                  ;   Once again, fancy terminology gets in the way of correct coding. When
 33597                                  ;   using next_free, start scanning AT THAT POINT and not the one following it.
 33598                                  ;   This fixes the boundary condition bug when only free = next_free = 2.
 33599                                  ;
 33600                                  ;       If we get to the end of the disk without satisfaction:
 33601                                  ;
 33602                                  ;           if (dpb_next_free == 2) then we've scanned the whole disk.
 33603                                  ;               return (insufficient_disk_space)
 33604                                  ;           ELSE
 33605                                  ;               dpb_next_free = 2; start scan over from the beginning.
 33606                                  ;
 33607                                  ;   Note that there is no multitasking interlock. There is no race when
 33608                                  ;   examining the entrys in an in-core FAT block since there will be no
 33609                                  ;   context switch. When UNPACK context switches while waiting for a FAT read
 33610                                  ;   we are done with any in-core FAT blocks, so again there is no race. The
 33611                                  ;   only special concern is that V2 and V3 MSDOS left the last allocated
 33612                                  ;   cluster as "00"; marking it EOF only when the entire alloc request was
 33613                                  ;   satisfied. We can't allow another activation to think this cluster is
 33614                                  ;   free, so we give it a special temporary mark to show that it is, indeed,
 33615                                  ;   allocated.
 33616                                  ;
 33617                                  ;   Note that when we run out of space this algorithem will scan from
 33618                                  ;   dpb_next_free to the end, then scan from cluster 2 through the end,
 33619                                  ;   redundantly scanning the later part of the disk. This only happens when
 33620                                  ;   we run out of space, so sue me.
 33621                                  ;
 33622                                  ;----+----+----+----+----+----+----+----+----+----+----+----+----+----+----;
 33623                                  ;            C  A  V  E  A  T     P  A  T  T  E  R  S  O  N                ;
 33624                                  ;                                                                          ;
 33625                                  ;   The use of FATBYT and RESTFATBYT is somewhat mysterious. Here is the
 33626                                  ;   explanation:
 33627                                  ;
 33628                                  ;   In the NUL file case (sf_firclus currently 0) ALLOCATE is called with
 33629                                  ;   entry BX = 0. What needs to be done in this case is to stuff the cluster
 33630                                  ;   number of the first cluster allocated in sf_firclus when the ALLOCATE is
 33631                                  ;   complete. THIS VALUE IS SAVED TEMPORARILY IN CLUSTER 0, HENCE THE CURRENT
 33632                                  ;   VALUE IN CLUSTER 0 MUST BE SAVED AND RESTORED. This is a side effect of
 33633                                  ;   the fact that PACK and UNPACK don't treat requests for clusters 0 and 1 as
 33634                                  ;   errors. This "stuff" is done by the call to PACK which is right before
 33635                                  ;   the
 33636                                  ;           LOOP   findfre         ; alloc more if needed
 33637                                  ;   instruction when the first cluster is allocated to the nul file. The
 33638                                  ;   value is recalled from cluster 0 and stored at sf_firclus at ads4:
 33639                                  ;
 33640                                  ;   This method is obviously useless (because it is non-reentrant) for
 33641                                  ;   multitasking, and will have to be changed. Storing the required value on
 33642                                  ;   the stack is recommended. Setting sf_firclus at the PACK of cluster 0
 33643                                  ;   (instead of actually doing the PACK) is BAD because it doesn't handle
 33644                                  ;   problems with INT 24 well.
