 52219                                  ;----------------------------------------------------------------------------
 52220                                  
 52221                                  ; We need to identify the parts of the data area that are relevant to tasks
 52222                                  ; and those that are relevant to the system as a whole.  Under 3.0, the system
 52223                                  ; data will be gathered with the system code.  The process data under 2.x will
 52224                                  ; be available for swapping and under 3.0 it will be allocated per-process.
 52225                                  ;
 52226                                  ; The data that is system data will be identified by [SYSTEM] in the comments
 52227                                  ; describing that data item.
 52228                                  
 52229                                  ;DOSDATA SEGMENT WORD PUBLIC 'DATA'
 52230                                  
 52231                                  ;
 52232                                  ; Table of routines for assignable devices
 52233                                  ;
 52234                                  ; MSDOS allows assignment if the following standard devices:
 52235                                  ;   stdin  (usually CON input)
 52236                                  ;   stdout (usually CON output)
 52237                                  ;   auxin  (usually AUX input)
 52238                                  ;   auxout (usually AUX output)
 52239                                  ;   stdlpt (usually PRN output)
 52240                                  ;
 52241                                  ; SPECIAL NOTE:
 52242                                  ;   Status of a file is a strange idea. We choose to handle it in this manner:
 52243                                  ;   If we're not at end-of-file, then we always say that we have a character.
 52244                                  ;   Otherwise, we return ^Z as the character and set the ZERO flag. In this
 52245                                  ;   manner we can support program written under the old DOS (they use ^Z as EOF
 52246                                  ;   on devices) and programs written under the new DOS (they use the ZERO flag
 52247                                  ;   as EOF).
